Option 3: 
We can modify `AdaptiveByteBufAllocator.usedHeapMemory()`, to let the current thread be able to count its own `threadLocalMagazine`'s memory usage, some code can be added to `AdaptiveByteBufAllocator.usedHeapMemory()` as following:
```
public long usedMemory() {
        long sum = 0;
        for (Chunk chunk : centralQueue) {
            sum += chunk.capacity();
        }
        for (Magazine magazine : magazines) {
            sum += magazine.usedMemory.get();
        }
        if (liveCachedMagazines != null) {
            for (Magazine magazine : liveCachedMagazines) {
                sum += magazine.usedMemory.get();
            }
            // Newly added code begin.
            if (!FastThreadLocalThread.willCleanupFastThreadLocals(Thread.currentThread())
                    && null != threadLocalMagazine && threadLocalMagazine.isSet()) {
                Object mag = threadLocalMagazine.get();
                if (mag != NO_MAGAZINE) {
                    sum += ((Magazine)mag).usedMemory.get();
                }
            }
            // Newly added code end.
        }
        return sum;
    }
```
But the current thread still can not count other threads's `threadLocalMagazine` memory usage, which is not ideal.

Option 4: 
If `FastThreadLocalThread.willCleanupFastThreadLocals(Thread.currentThread()) == false`, then we will NOT use `threadLocalMagazine`, this needs to modify `threadLocalMagazine`'s `initialValue()` method as following:
```
@Override
protected Object initialValue() {
    if (cachedMagazinesNonEventLoopThreads || ThreadExecutorMap.currentExecutor() != null) {
        if (!FastThreadLocalThread.willCleanupFastThreadLocals(Thread.currentThread())) {
            // Log a warning: To prevent leak, we will NOT use threadLocalMagazine.
            return NO_MAGAZINE;
        }
        Magazine mag = new Magazine(AdaptivePoolingAllocator.this, false);
        liveMagazines.add(mag);
        return mag;
    }
    return NO_MAGAZINE;
}
```
I think this is a better option, since it's rare and discourage to set `willCleanupFastThreadLocals` to `false` when using `FastThreadLocalThread` to run a wrapped runnable task, as the java doc stated:
https://github.com/netty/netty/blob/a0e67671651a99977391c5552dd90e7bc147308a/common/src/main/java/io/netty/util/concurrent/FastThreadLocalThread.java#L29-L30

@franz1981 WDYT?
